[[画像:Yatagarasu-jinja Torii.jpg|thumb|250px|Entrance torii]]

'''Yatagarasu Shrine''' (やたがらすじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Uda|Q863747|WD=Q863747|1=Uda, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|WD=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|lt=small Shikinaisha|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=small Shikinaisha|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} listed in the '{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=UNKNOWN}}'. Its former rank was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=kensha|1=Ken-sha|WD=Q90139226}}.

=== Enshrined deity ===
It enshrines {{ill|lt=Kamo Taketsunumi-no-Mikoto|Q11634939|WD=Q11634939|lt=Taketsunumi-no-Mikoto|1=Kamotaketsunumi no Mikoto}} ({{ill|lt=Yatagarasu|Q745463|WD=Q745463|1=Yatagarasu}}).

=== History ===
In the '{{ill|lt=Shoku Nihongi|Q611399|WD=Q611399|1=Shoku Nihongi}}', in the reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Monmu|Q357246|WD=Q357246|1=Emperor Monmu}}, there is an entry that in {{ill|lt=Keiun|Q428753|WD=Q428753|1=Keiun}} 2 ({{ill|lt=705|Q23504|WD=Q23504|1=705}}), Yatagarasu-sha was worshiped, and this is taken as the founding of this shrine<ref>Entry for day bōjutsu (9th) in 9th month.</ref>. In documentary terms, it is the first shrine in Japan to worship Yatagarasu as a deity.

Also, according to the 'Shinsen Shōjiroku,' when {{ill|lt=Emperor Jinmu|Q200188|WD=Q200188|1=Emperor Jimmu}} moved east to Yamato, Taketsunumi-no-Mikoto transformed into "Yatagarasu" and guided the stalled imperial party through the mountains of {{ill|lt=Kumano|Q6443450|WD=Q6443450|1=Kumano region}} to Yamato, contributing to imperial victory.

Because of this history, it was revered since ancient times as a {{ill|lt=war deity|Q11637440|WD=Q11637440|1=Military god}}, and in the {{ill|lt=Nanboku-chō period|Q264012|WD=Q264012|lt=Nanboku-chō period|1=Nanboku-chō period}}, the shrine is said to have greatly prospered under deep devotion of {{ill|lt=Emperor Go-Daigo|Q313942|WD=Q313942|1=Emperor Go-Daigo}}<ref>"Brief Origin of Yatagarasu Shrine," Bunsei 13 year of Kanoe-Tora, Ōe no Toshitsune.</ref>.

However, after decline of the {{ill|lt=Southern Court (Japan)|Q3001082|WD=Q3001082|lt=Southern Court|1=Southern Court}} and repeated war damage, it fell near abolition until the mid-{{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, and it is said "yatagarasu" became colloquially slurred to "otogorosu"<ref>Hayashi Sōho, 'Washū Kyūseki Yūkō,' Enpō 9.</ref>.

Later, in {{ill|lt=Bunsei|Q1327119|WD=Q1327119|1=Bunsei}} years of the Edo period, priests of {{ill|lt=Kamomioya Shrine|Q701620|WD=Q701620|1=Shimogamo Shrine}} (Shimogamo-sha) in {{ill|lt=Kyoto|Q740246|WD=Q740246|1=Kyōto}} took notice, and through their efforts and cooperation of local volunteers, revival was achieved. It is said the honden was rebuilt into current {{ill|lt=kasuga-zukuri|Q3193781|WD=Q3193781|1=Kasuga-zukuri}} style around this time (the stone small shrine of the former honden still remains beside the honden).

After that, for annual grand festivals, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=heihaku envoys|1=UNKNOWN}} were sent from Shimogamo-sha and rites held, but because such grand rites with envoys were too heavy a burden for local parishioners then numbering only about nine households, and due guidance from Nara prefectural authorities concerned the shrine might be treated as an outside-precinct massha of Shimogamo-sha, Shimogamo participation was discontinued in early Meiji<ref>"Uda District Historical Materials."</ref>.

Later, in {{ill|lt=Taishō|Q329174|WD=Q329174|1=Taishō era}} 3 ({{ill|lt=1917|Q2092|WD=Q2092|1=1917}}), due to the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shrine Merger Ordinance|1=UNKNOWN}}, nearby guardian shrines came to be worshiped here, causing sudden revival.

In {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}}, related to {{ill|lt=2600th Imperial Year commemorative events|Q5366450|WD=Q5366450|1=2600th Anniversary Celebrations of the Japanese Empire}}, it was promoted to kensha, and precinct expansion and improvement were carried out. It has continued to the present.

